        "shortInsight": "When specifying an array's type, you can use any built-in types, inline types, or type aliases:    And if you try to update the array with an item ...",
        "teaching": "When specifying an array's type, you can use any built-in types, inline types, or type aliases:\n\n```ts twoslash\ntype Album = {\n  artist: string;\n  title: string;\n  year: number;\n};\n\nlet selectedDiscography: Album[] = [\n  {\n    artist: \"The Beatles\",\n    title: \"Rubber Soul\",\n    year: 1965,\n  },\n  {\n    artist: \"The Beatles\",\n    title: \"Revolver\",\n    year: 1966,\n  },\n];\n```\n\nAnd if you try to update the array with an item that doesn't match the type, TypeScript will give you an error:\n\n```ts twoslash\n// @errors: 2353\ntype Album = {\n  artist: string;\n  title: string;\n  year: number;\n};\n\nlet selectedDiscography: Album[] = [\n  {\n    artist: \"The Beatles\",\n    title: \"Rubber Soul\",\n    year: 1965,\n  },\n  {\n    artist: \"The Beatles\",\n    title: \"Revolver\",\n    year: 1966,\n  },\n];\n\n// ---cut---\nselectedDiscography.push({ name: \"Karma\", type: \"cat\" });\n```",
