        "shortInsight": "Your first instinct will be to check if response.data is truthy.",
        "teaching": "Your first instinct will be to check if `response.data` is truthy.\n\n```ts twoslash\n// @errors: 2339\ntype APIResponse =\n  | {\n      data: {\n        id: string;\n      };\n    }\n  | {\n      error: string;\n    };\n\n// ---cut---\nconst handleResponse = (response: APIResponse) => {\n  if (response.data) {\n    return response.data.id;\n  } else {\n    throw new Error(response.error);\n  }\n};\n```\n\nBut you'll get an error. This is because `response.data` is only available on one of the members of the union. TypeScript doesn't know that `response` is the one with `data` on it.",
        "realLifeExample": "Here is a code example from the book:\n\n```ts\n// @errors: 2339\ntype APIResponse =\n  | {\n      data: {\n        id: string;\n      };\n    }\n  | {\n      error: string;\n    };\n\n// ---cut---\nconst handleResponse = (response: APIResponse) => {\n  if (response.data) {\n    return response.data.id;\n  } else {\n    throw new Error(response.error);\n  }\n};\n```",
