        "id": "ts-book-141",
        "category": "Total TypeScript",
        "topic": "Chapter 5: Unions Literals And Narrowing",
        "subtopic": "Option 2: Using `in`",
        "shortInsight": "We can use an in operator to check if a specific key exists on response.",
        "teaching": "We can use an `in` operator to check if a specific key exists on `response`.\n\nIn this example, it would check for the key `data`:\n\n```ts twoslash\ntype APIResponse =\n  | {\n      data: {\n        id: string;\n      };\n    }\n  | {\n      error: string;\n    };\n\n// ---cut---\nconst handleResponse = (response: APIResponse) => {\n  if (\"data\" in response) {\n    return response.data.id;\n  } else {\n    throw new Error(response.error);\n  }\n};\n```\n\nIf the `response` isn't the one with `data` on it, then it must be the one with `error`, so we can throw an `Error` with the error message.\n\nYou can check this out by hovering over `.data` and `.error` in each of the branches of the `if` statement. TypeScript will show you that it knows the type of `response` in each case.\n\nUsing `in` here gives us a great way to narrow down objects that might have different keys from one another.",
        "realLifeExample": "Here is a code example from the book:\n\n```ts\ntype APIResponse =\n  | {\n      data: {\n        id: string;\n      };\n    }\n  | {\n      error: string;\n    };\n\n// ---cut---\nconst handleResponse = (response: APIResponse) => {\n  if (\"data\" in response) {\n    return response.data.id;\n  } else {\n    throw new Error(response.error);\n  }\n};\n```",
