        "id": "ts-book-203",
        "category": "Total TypeScript",
        "topic": "Chapter 6: Objects",
        "subtopic": "Solution 4: Dynamic Key Support",
        "shortInsight": "The obvious answer is to change the key's type to string | number | symbol:    However, there's a much more succinct solution.",
        "teaching": "The obvious answer is to change the `key`'s type to `string | number | symbol`:\n\n```typescript\nconst hasKey = (obj: object, key: string | number | symbol) => {\n  return obj.hasOwnProperty(key);\n};\n```\n\nHowever, there's a much more succinct solution.\n\nHovering over `hasOwnProperty` shows us the type definition:\n\n```typescript\n(method) Object.hasOwnProperty(v: PropertyKey): boolean\n```\n\nRecall that the `PropertyKey` type represents every possible value a key can have. This means we can use it as the type for the key parameter:\n\n```typescript\nconst hasKey = (obj: object, key: PropertyKey) => {\n  return obj.hasOwnProperty(key);\n};\n```\n\nBeautiful.",
        "realLifeExample": "Here is a code example from the book:\n\n```ts\nconst hasKey = (obj: object, key: string | number | symbol) => {\n  return obj.hasOwnProperty(key);\n};\n```",
