        "topic": "Chapter 12: The Weird Parts",
        "subtopic": "Arrow Functions",
        "shortInsight": "Arrow functions, unlike, function keyword functions, can't be annotated with a this parameter:    This is because arrow functions can't inherit thi...",
        "teaching": "Arrow functions, unlike, `function` keyword functions, can't be annotated with a `this` parameter:\n\n```ts twoslash\n// @errors: 2730\nconst sellAlbum = (this: { title: string; sales: number }) => {\n  // implementation\n};\n```\n\nThis is because arrow functions can't inherit `this` from the scope where they're called. Instead, they inherit `this` from the scope where they're _defined_. This means they can only access `this` when defined inside classes.",
        "realLifeExample": "Here is a code example from the book:\n\n```ts\n// @errors: 2730\nconst sellAlbum = (this: { title: string; sales: number }) => {\n  // implementation\n};\n```",
        "quiz": {
            "question": "Choose the best answer to complete the sentence:\n\n\"This ______ they can only access `this` when defined inside classes.?\"",
            "options": [
                "means",
                "Conditional Types",
                "Declaration Merging",
                "Type Assertions"
            ],
            "answer": "means"
        }
