        "shortInsight": "An alternative solution would be to use declare global with the interface directly in the index.ts file:    Either approach will work, but often ke...",
        "teaching": "An alternative solution would be to use `declare global` with the interface directly in the `index.ts` file:\n\n```tsx\n// index.ts\nconst state = window.DEBUG.getState();\n\ntype test = Expect<Equal<typeof state, { id: string }>>;\n\ndeclare global {\n  interface Window {\n    DEBUG: {\n      getState: () => {\n        id: string;\n      };\n    };\n  }\n}\n```\n\nEither approach will work, but often keeping the global types in a separate file can make them easier to find.",
