        "id": "ts-book-548",
        "category": "Total TypeScript",
        "topic": "Chapter 16: The Utils Folder",
        "subtopic": "What Makes A Function Generic?",
        "shortInsight": "A function is generic if it declares a type parameter.",
        "teaching": "A function is generic if it declares a type parameter. Here's a generic function that takes a type parameter `T`:\n\n```typescript\nfunction identity<T>(arg: T): T {\n  //                 ^^^ Type parameter\n  return arg;\n}\n```\n\nWe can use the function keyword, or use arrow function syntax:\n\n```typescript\nconst identity = <T>(arg: T): T => arg;\n```\n\nWe can even declare a generic function as a type:\n\n```typescript\ntype Identity = <T>(arg: T) => T;\n\nconst identity: Identity = (arg) => arg;\n```\n\nNow, we can pass a type argument to `identity`:\n\n```typescript\nidentity<number>(42);\n```",
        "realLifeExample": "Here is a code example from the book:\n\n```ts\nfunction identity<T>(arg: T): T {\n  //                 ^^^ Type parameter\n  return arg;\n}\n```",
        "quiz": {
            "question": "Choose the best answer to complete the sentence:\n\n\"A ______ is generic if it declares a type parameter?\"",
            "options": [
                "Generics",
                "Type Narrowing",
                "Type Inference",
                "function"
            ],
            "answer": "function"
        }
